&quot;Arthur Schnitzler, born in Vienna, 1862, to Jewish migrants from Hungary, became a physician, playwright and writer of fiction, and was one of the members of Vienna&rsquo;s famed Jung Wien. He wrote in his autobiography about the time he was a medical student in the early 1880s, in which he preferred to meet his friends outside the University of Vienna &ldquo;on a more neutral ground, in a more congenial atmosphere.&rdquo; The &ldquo;neutral ground,&rdquo; for Schintzler was &ldquo;usually some coffeehouse, like Café Central, where I would spend hours reading the papers, playing billiard and dominoes, and...chess, with a gray- bearded Polish [
                    i.e. east European
                ]Jewish man.&rdquo; Schnitzler wrote that in spite of being a medical student, he felt &ldquo;altogether so much more at home&rdquo; in the atmosphere of the café, &ldquo;especially when there was a bohemian air about it.&rdquo;47&quot; (99)

The Swiss-owned <a data-size="large" data-align="left" data-caption="title" data-annotations="" resource="media/cafe-fanconi" href="http://ec2-52-11-202-148.us-west-2.compute.amazonaws.com/media/cafefanconiodessa_ueF1IOp.jpg">Café Fanconi</a> was opened in 1872.&nbsp;&ldquo;By the end of the nineteenth century,&rdquo; writes the historian Steven Zipperstein, &ldquo;little was left&hellip;of [
                    Odessa&rsquo;s
                ]Italians or French influences than a smattering of splendid, popular cafés&mdash;Café Fanconi was the best well-known.&rdquo;

According to the memoir of his friend Israel Trivus, one of Odessa&rsquo;s Zionists, <a data-size="small" data-align="right" data-caption="title" data-annotations="" resource="vladimir-yevgenyevich-jabotinsky-zeev-jabotinsky" href="http://www.encyclopediaofukraine.com/pic%5CZ%5CH%5CZhabotinsky%20Vladimir.jpg">Jabotinsky</a>&nbsp;said that in the <strong>Greek Café Ambarzaki</strong>, &ldquo;there is an aroma of Asia, . . . but it creates an ambiance that takes you up to the sky, where there is no limit to your thought and imagination.&rdquo;<br /><br />Playing on the Greek name of the café, Jabotinsky claimed that when he got to know this &ldquo;lofty institution&rdquo; well enough, he finally understood &ldquo;the ancient Olympus, where one could enjoy ambrosia and nectar,&rdquo; and that &ldquo;God&rsquo;s nectar is really a fragrant cup of Turkish-style coffee, and ambrosia is rahat lokum [
                        Turkish delight
                    ]and halva.&rdquo; However, it was not just the divine food and drink that Jabotinsky was attracted to but the conversation with the Greek owner of the café. He was enthralled with the visitors&rsquo; talk, which, according to Trivus, revolved around Greek and Jewish national movements and the emerging Zionist movement, as well as around the glories of Odessa, Pushkin&rsquo;s poems (which Jabotinsky recited from memory), the city, and its cafés.

